5    /**
6    * Superclass for elements in a hierarchical data structure.
7    * There are two types of DataNodes - DataValueNode representing
8    * a value (leaf nodes) and DataGroupNode for internal nodes.
9    * The abstract DataNode specifies the common interface. All
10    * nodes have a name. There are two key recursive boolean
11    * attributes which can be checked any place in the hierarchy -
12    * <i>modified</i> (whether any value is changed) and
13    * <i>valid</i> (whether all values are valid). The latter is
14    * based on meta data, which can optionally be added to data
15    * nodes in the form of MetaNode objects. A Traverser
16    * interface can be used to run custom operations on all nodes.
17    * <p>
18    * A DataNode tree can be accessed directly, but the recommended
19    * interface for external code is DataHandle, which allows working
20    * with paths in the tree structure, and which can add transaction
21    * handling and subscription to changes.
22    *
23    * @author Lars Thomas Boye, Tellu AS
24    */

45    * enterGroup is called when first encountering a group
46    * node. Each child node is then entered in turn, and
47    * finally exitGroup is called once the recursive
48    * processing of child nodes is finished. processItem
49    * is called for each value node encountered.
50    * The methods can return false to stop traversal.
51    *
52    * @see DataNode#process(Traverser)
53    */

113    /**
114    * Assign MetaData to the DataNode. Only a MetaGroupNode can
115    * be assigned to a DataGroupNode, and a MetaItemNode to a
116    * DataValueNode. MetaNodes can have a tree structure matching
117    * that of the DataNodes, and this method will set meta nodes
118    * recursively to child data nodes. But this will throw a
119    * DataRestrictionException if any existing nodes are illegal
120    * according to the MetaNodes. This happens if there is a
121    * mismatch between the type of a value in the nodes and the
122    * corresponding meta being set, or if there are multiple
123    * nodes of a name where the meta cardinality only allows one.
124    * If an exception is thrown, the DataNode may be in an
125    * invalid state as some of meta may have been applied, so it
126    * should be discarded. External code should primarily use
127    * this method on the root of a tree, otherwise meta data is
128    * best handled indirectly through the other classes of this
129    * package or by a DataModel, to make sure it stays consistent
130    * with the data and other meta.
131    *
132    * Missing nodes which are required
133    * according to meta are created, with any default values
134    * specified by the meta nodes.
135    *
136    * @param meta MetaNode to assign, or null for none
137    */

189    /**
190    * Requirements may be specified on the value of a data item
191    * (data type, whether a value is required, range/length, etc.).
192    * A value node is valid if its value satisfies any requirements,
193    * or if there are no requirements. Cardinality - how many nodes
194    * there can/must be - is another type of requirement, which can
195    * be specified on all nodes. This is checked on group nodes,
196    * returning false if a required node is missing or there are
197    * more than one node where meta doesn't allow multiple. Group
198    * nodes are only valid if all children are valid.
199    *
200    * @return true if data in/under this node meets all requirements
201    */
202    public abstract boolean isValid();
203   
204    /**
205    * Have a Traverser process the DataNodes. It traverses the
206    * node tree, calling enterGroup on each group node as it is
207    * entered and exitGroup after the recursive processing of
208    * all child nodes. processItem is called for each value node.
209    * If a Traverser method returns false, meaning it doesn't
210    * need to process any more nodes, the process stops and this
211    * method also returns false. Returning true means all nodes
212    * have been processed.
213    *
214    * @param t
215    * @return false if traversal is ended prematurely
216    */
217    public abstract boolean process(Traverser t);

233    /**
234    * Copy method with all options. The cloned node is a deep copy
235    * with respect to the tree of nodes, recursively cloning child
236    * nodes. It is shallow with respect to values in leaf nodes,
237    * copying references to the same value objects. modified flags
238    * are false in the new node.
239    * <p>
240    * It can clone all nodes, or only child nodes where isModified
241    * is true. The node the method is called on is cloned in any
242    * case, but child nodes will only be included if they are
243    * modified. Note that if any part of an array (multiples nodes
244    * with same name, and/or cardinality 0/1-n) is modified, the
245    * array is considered modified, and all nodes are cloned.
246    * <p>
247    * Can't keepMeta if name is changed. Can throw DataRestrictionException
248    * if meta doesn't match.
249    *
250    * @param newName name of cloned node, null to keep old name
251    * @param modifiedOnly true to only clone modified child nodes
252    * @param keepMeta true to keep references to meta-data
253    * @return clone of this node
254    */
255    public abstract DataNode cloneNode(String newName, boolean modifiedOnly, boolean keepMeta);
